# Parallel Development Workflow

Enable concurrent development of the same feature using multiple AI agents in isolated git worktrees.

## When to Use Parallel Development
- Testing multiple implementation strategies
- Comparing different UI/UX approaches
- Validating architectural decisions
- Split testing features for optimal results

## Setup Pattern

### Initialize Parallel Worktrees
Use the init-parallel commands to create isolated development environments:
1. Create `trees/` directory
2. Generate multiple git worktrees (`trees/feature-name-1/`, `trees/feature-name-2/`, etc.)
3. Each gets unique ports (5174, 5175, 5176)
4. Copy environment files and install dependencies

### Execute Parallel Development
1. Each agent works in isolation in their assigned worktree
2. Agents implement the same specification with different approaches
3. Focus on code changes only (no server/client startup)
4. Document results in `RESULTS.md` at workspace root

## Workflow Commands

### Initialization
```bash
# Create 3 parallel worktrees for feature development
git worktree add -b feature-name-1 ./trees/feature-name-1
git worktree add -b feature-name-2 ./trees/feature-name-2  
git worktree add -b feature-name-3 ./trees/feature-name-3
```

### Verification
```bash
git worktree list  # Verify all trees created properly
eza trees --tree --level 3  # View structure
```

## Agent Instructions
- Implement the engineering plan in your assigned workspace
- Create comprehensive `RESULTS.md` documenting all changes
- Focus on code implementation, avoid starting servers
- Work independently without cross-agent communication

## Comparison and Selection
After parallel execution:
1. Review each agent's `RESULTS.md` file
2. Compare implementation approaches
3. Test different solutions in isolation
4. Select best implementation or merge approaches
5. Clean up unused worktrees

## Integration with ClaudeCode
Perfect for ClaudeCode parallel execution:
